flowRoot.flowPara: Jigsaw puzzles are a classic style of puzzle created by mounting an image on a sheet of material (wood, cardstock) and then using a jigsaw to cut out the pieces. The earliest jigsaw puzzles used a thick sheet of wood and the pieces were cut by hand or with an electric jigsaw, a labor intensive process. Modern mass-produced puzzles use a cardstock type material instead of wood and an expensive metal die to cut out all the pieces at once which greatly speeds up production.

Today we are going to create a puzzle a different way using a lasercutter. The lasercutter will raster an image of your choosing and then cut out the pieces. This method is a nice compromise between the traditional and mass-produced methods, making it perfect for custom gifts and puzzle prototypes.

1. Open up a web browser and navigate to images.google.com. Find an image to use for your puzzle and download to the desktop. Keep in mind we want each puzzle piece to have a portion of the image in it (no blank pieces). Square-ish, high contrast black and white images work best. You can also add custom text or shapes later to fill out your design.
2. Download the 5" x 5" puzzle template from the Makerlab website and open it in Inkscape.

3. In Inkscape: File > Import to import the image. Resize the image to fit inside your puzzle template. It can help to convert image to greyscale to increase contrast: Filters > Color (greyscale, lightness-contrast).
4. Add any additional text or shapes to fill out your design. Make sure there is something overlapping each puzzle piece.

5. When your design is ready, we will send the file to the lasercutter from Inkscape to Retina Engrave. Be aware that rastering large fill areas will take quite some time. You can lower the DPI to 250 to speed up the process and select half-tone dithering to increase contrast.

6|.For wood, make sure to raster with enough power so the image is darker than the cut lines. After rastering, cut the red lines before the blue outline so the pieces don't fall through while cutting.
